SIMPLE: shady
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shady
<hw>Shad"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Shadier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Shadiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Abounding in shade or
shades; overspread with shade; causing shade.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>shady</qex> trees cover him with their shadow.</q>
<rj><qau>Job. xl. 22.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And Amaryllis fills the <qex>shady</qex> groves.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Sheltered from the glare of light or sultry
heat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cast it also that you may have rooms <qex>shady</qex> for summer
and warm for winter.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to shade or darkness;</def>
<specif>hence,</specif> <def>unfit to be seen or known; of questionable
character; unsavory; equivocal; dubious, corrupt, or criminal; <as>as, a
<ex>shady</ex> character</as>; -- of people or activities.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>shady</xex> business.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>London Sat. Rev.</au></rj></p>

<p><q><qex>Shady</qex> characters, disreputable, criminal.</q>
<rj><qau>London Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>On the shady side of</b></col>, <cd>on the thither side
of; as, <xex>on the shady side of</xex> fifty; that is, more than
fifty.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>To keep shady</b></col>,
<cd>to stay in concealment; also, to be reticent.</cd>
<mark>[Slang]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shaffle</ent>⟦br⟧
